<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;has been recently identified.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains detailed information about the work you are citing.
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
In the footnote, provide all known details of the primary source (as given by the secondary source) followed by <strong>quoted in</strong>, and then give the full details of the secondary source that you consulted.
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm double-line-spacing">
	<span class="smaller">1. Bo Peep, <em>Search through the High Country</em> (Wellington: Kowhai Press, 2025): 23, quoted in Boyd Blue, <em>Free Range: A History of Farming Practice in New Zealand</em> (Auckland: University Books, 2056), 234.</span>
</blockquote>
